 to implement classes like HASH, DH, and SignatureRSA, and whether I could make them deterministic. Should I instantiate them using Class.forName in DHG1? It seems I could simplify DHG1, but I'd still require a Session. The public API Session.connect also uses Class.forName, which complicates things. I’m wondering if I can test with stub classes, but it looks like creating source stubs or replacements for library API types isn’t allowed.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating server exchange hashing**\\n\\nI'm noting a potential flaw in our server exchange hash with DHG1. It uses 'f' after calling dh.setF(f), then derives K using dh.getK. I'm wondering if K, as an MPInt in H, requires a byte[] conversion that might include a leading zero. Also, I'm curious about whether unsignedFixedLength is suitable for sharedSecret, given that JSch JCE DH.getK might strip the leading zero or apply a fixed length. I should read more about DH to clarify this.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_kxwlT3ThxYq3hfMoskxbrnHv|fc_09f6da4d157af040016a110ac83eec819dba2c049a264d6059", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge2/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/com.jcraft/jsch/0.1.27/main/extracted/com/jcraft/jsch/jce/DH.java"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1753, "output": 898, "cacheRead": 35840, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 38491, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1779501753834, "responseId": "resp_09f6da4d157af040016a110aba54c0819d9175e7b4b08a67c4"}}
